 peculiar group of prognostic guides and calendars, in Latin and Old English, found in an eleventh-century manuscript from Christ Church, Canterbury; they are collated with related versions in both Anglo-Saxon and continental manuscripts. A lengthy introduction and commentary examine the transmission and translation of these texts, and shed light on their origins and uses in late Anglo-Saxon monastic culture. ROY LIUZZA is Professor of English at the University of Tennessee, Knoxville.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aForecastingvEarly works to 1800. 0aPropheciesvEarly works to 1800. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCalendars.  aDreams.  aMedicine.  aMedieval Prognostic Texts.  aMonastic Life.  aPredicting the Future.  aPrognostic Guides.1 aLiuzza, R. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615928240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846159282423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846159282/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles